In any case, and according to the climatological hurricane trajectories in the North Atlantic, the waters of the Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) of Cuba can be aected by TCs during the entire hurricane season ( http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/climo/ ).

Considering the maximum sustained wind speed (i.e., the highest one-minute average wind at an el- evation of 10 m with an unobstructed exposure at a particular point in time, http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/ aboutgloss.shtml ), TCs can be classied into the following categories: tropical depression, tropical storm and hurricane, depending on whether sustained winds are, respectively, lower than 18 m s

In the same way, of the 38 TCs that have crossed the EEZ of Cuba in 1998{2016, 18 were hurricanes, 11 tropical storms and 9 tropical depressions according to the National Hurri- cane Center (NHC) ( http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/ ).

The shapele of the EEZ of Cuba was obtained from the world EEZ product (version 9) ( http://www.marineregions.org/downloads.php ) of the Flanders Marine Institute, where the inner boundary of the EEZ (i.e., the baseline) in Figure 1C is used as a proxy for the low-water line.

Specically, we included in our study TCs that at some point of their trajectory within the EEZ reached the hurricane category, i.e., 18 hurricanes according to the NHC reports ( http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/ ).

We obtained the hurricane trajectories from the International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS v03r03) (Knapp et al., 2010) (ftp://eclipse.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/ibtracs/v03r09/all/shp/ ).

We assessed the oceanographic variability along the hurricane trajectory in 120 km radius disks centered at every consecutive 6-hourly hurricane position (http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/hurdat2.html ) within the EEZ.

Indeed, the outer spiral rainbands of almost all analysed hurricanes covered the entire EEZ, as was conrmed by a visual in- spection of the GOES-13 visible satellite images ( http://www.goes.noaa.gov/browsh.html ).

Thus, we used the Cross-Calibrated Multi-Platform (CCMP, version 2.0) 6-hourly gridded ocean vector wind (to a height of 10 m) data (Atlas et al., 2011), produced by Remote Sensing Systems (data available at ftp://ftp.remss.com/ccmp/v02.0/ ), which have been used in other studies assessing TC eects (e.g., Fu et al., 2014; Peng and Li, 2015; Lin and Oey, 2016).

We derived SST data using the Operational SST and Sea Ice Analysis (OSTIA) Reprocessed (1998{ 2007) and Near Real Time (2008{2016) Level 4 SST products (Donlon et al., 2012) provided by the Copernicus Marine Environment Monitoring Service ( http://marine.copernicus.eu ).

Infrared radiometer data The chl-a images were obtained from the multisatellite merged global data of the GlobColour project ( http://globcolour.info ), developed, validated, and distributed by ACRI-ST, France.

We also used the data of the coloured dissolved and detrital organic material absorption coecient at 443 nm (CDM) computed with the Garver, Siegel and Maritorena model (GSM, Maritorena et al., 2010) and the phytoplankton absorption coecient at 443 nm (a ph), provided by MODIS Aqua ( https://oceancolor.gsfc.

Altimeter data Given the geographical location of the EEZ of Cuba and the complex system of marine currents in the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea LMEs, which likely inuence the distribution of chl-a, we used the Salto/DUACS gridded multimission altimeter products processed and distributed by the Copernicus Marine Environment Monitoring Service ( http://marine.copernicus.eu ).

Considering that the upward trans- port of nitrate depends not only on the mixing, but also on the depth from which nitrate origi- nates (Omand and Mahadevan, 2015), we used the nitrate proles data of the World Ocean Atlas 2013, version 2 ( https://www.nodc.noaa.gov/OC5/woa13/ ), to estimate the climatological depth of the nitracline (DNO 3) and considered this feature as an important biogeochemical factor constraining the biological response after the TC passage (Menkes et al., 2016).

The used product is a set of objectively analysed (11) climatological elds of in situ nitrate concentration at standard depths for monthly composite periods ( https://www.nodc.noaa.gov/OC5/woa13/ ).

The depth of the deep chlorophyll maximum (DCM) is also an important factor con- tributing to the chl-a increase after the TC passage (Menkes et al., 2016), but we did not include it in our analysis since only a limited number of chl-a proles from the World Ocean Atlas Database were available for the EEZ of Cuba and also they only extended to depths of 100 m. 2.3.3 Data derived from the National Hurricane Center NHC best track reported times and positions were used ( http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/ hur- dat2.html ) to calculate the transit speed of the hurricanes within the EEZ of Cuba, according to the procedure outlined by Babin et al.

On the other hand, we used the NOAA's Historical Hurricane Tracks online tool ( https://coast.noaa.gov/hurricanes ) to assign the Sar-Simpson category to hur- ricanes within the EEZ on the basis of their maximum sustained wind speed reported by the NHC (http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/hurdat2.html ).

The DAP peaks during those weeks result from the pre-storm rainfalls of Lili (2002) and Ike (2008), and the post-storm rain- falls of Paloma (2008), which weakened to a tropical depression and became nearly stationary over Cuba, ( http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/AL172008 Paloma.pdf ) leaving the EEZ only 6 days after its entrance.
